## Report Outline (Revised): Hybrid LLM Deployment

**1. Introduction**
   - The hybrid model: local LLMs + cloud APIs working together
   - Why organizations don't pick one — both have a role
   - Defining local LLMs in practice

**2. The Hybrid Architecture Pattern**
   - **Local path**: sensitive RAG, internal copilots, code assistants, factory/edge inference
   - **Cloud path**: frontier-tier capabilities, burst traffic, general-purpose tasks
   - Decision flow: how organizations route queries between paths
   - The "data stays close to where it's generated" principle

**3. Why Hybrid, Not Pure Local**
   - Local: privacy, low latency, compliance-sensitive workflows, edge operations
   - Cloud: capability ceiling, cost efficiency for peak demand, rapid frontier updates
   - Trade-offs that drive the split

**4. Operational Drivers for Local Inference**
   - Latency — no API round-trip, critical for real-time workflows (factory line, retail kiosk)
   - Data governance — proprietary data never leaves premises
   - Reliability — works when network goes down
   - Cost predictability — fixed hardware vs. per-token billing at scale

**5. Common Local Deployment Patterns**
   - **RAG-based knowledge systems** — document Q&A over internal wikis, SOPs
   - **Internal copilots** — tailored to company tone, tools, domain vocabulary
   - **Code assistance** — private codebases, no leakage to external API
   - **Edge workflows** — factory floor inspection, retail assistant, field agent tools
   - **Compliance pipelines** — healthcare PHI, financial records, government data

**6. Hardware & Model Stack**
   - What fit on a workstation today (RTX 3060/4080/5080 class)
   - Quantized 7B–13B models as the sweet spot for on-device
   - When multi-GPU or CPU offloading becomes necessary
   - Server-class deployments for higher-capability needs

**7. Use Cases That Favor Pure Local vs. Hybrid**
   - Strongest local cases: RAG on classified docs, PHI-sensitive workflows, isolated factory floors
   - Best hybrid cases: general Q&A routing to cloud + local fallback, burst capacity overflow
   - What shouldn't go local yet (models that still need frontier-tier reasoning)

**8. Implementation Considerations**
   - Model selection for the target workload
   - GPU memory sizing (4-bit vs. 8-bit, context length impact)
   - RAG pipeline setup (embedding models, chunking, retrieval strategies)
   - Monitoring, update cadence, and prompt governance
   - Vendor-neutral approach (open weights vs. proprietary open models)

**9. Limitations**
   - Capability gap — 7B local models vs. frontier cloud models on complex tasks
   - Hardware cost at enterprise scale
   - Operational burden: versioning, security hardening, monitoring
   - Prompt injection risks that persist even on-prem

**10. Future Outlook**
   - Smaller models catching up on reasoning/benchmarks
   - Hardware improvements (more VRAM, faster memory)
   - Regulatory tailwinds (data sovereignty laws, AI compliance mandates)
   - The likely end state: most enterprises run some mix

---

This puts hybrid as the thesis, operational concerns as the driver, and maps the landscape without overselling local-as-replacement. Does this hit the mark? I can start drafting sections or deepening any area — your call on what to tackle first.
